","1282–1322":"1282–1322","1228–1261":"1228–1261","about 1282":"about 1282","about 1280":"about 1280","before 12 March 1282":"before 12 March 1282","before 1278":"before 1278","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1322":"1322","1311":"1311","1256":"1256","1299":"1299","9 August 1279":"9 August 1279","1353":"1353","1254":"1254","about 1254":"about 1254","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grelley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of Irish   Crilly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crilly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghailligh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghailleach</i>’. Compare   Crawley  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":5,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"1